      <title>Researchers uncover bacteria's drug defense system</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANResearchers have discovered how a group of drug-resistant bacteria defend against medicine.Gram-negative bacteria have an additional outer membrane that makes them strong against antibiotics and responsible for serious drug-resistant infections. This outer membrane is made up of sugars, proteins, and lipids.How the sugars and proteins are made inside the cell and then transported to the outer membrane is understood, but how lipids get there was not.Researchers, led by Dr. Tim Knowles at the University of Birmingham, investigated the crystal structure of a protein called MlaC and found a mechanism that seems to open and close a pocket that lipids bind to. According to New Atlas, this controls inner-cell functions that dictate when lipids are sent to the outer membrane. This discovery, researchers believe, could one day lead to new drug design that can stop the outer membrane from forming and better treat infectious diseases.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Gram-negative bacteria have a protective outer membrane2. The outer membrane is made up of sugar, protein, and lipids3. Lipids are transported via a pocket mechanism4. New drugs could stop the outer membrane from formingVOICEOVER (in English): "Gram-negative bacteria have an additional outer membrane that makes them strong against antibiotics and responsible for serious drug-resistant infections. "This outer membrane is made up of sugars, proteins, and lipids." "How the sugars and proteins are made inside the cell and then transported to the outer membrane is understood, but how lipids get there was not.""Researchers, led by Dr. Tim Knowles at the University of Birmingham, investigated the crystal structure of a protein called MlaC and found a mechanism that seems to open and close a pocket that lipids bind to." "According to New Atlas, this controls inner-cell functions that dictate when lipids are sent to the outer membrane. "This discovery, researchers believe, could one day lead to new drug design that can stop the outer membrane from forming and better treat infectious diseases."SOURCES: NEW ATLAS, THE UNIVERSITY OF QUEENSLAND, NATUREhttps://newatlas.com/bacteria-defense-system-better-drugs/60629/https://www.uq.edu.au/news/article/2019/07/bacterial-defence-construction-revealed-step-forward-new-antibioticshttps://www.nature.com/articles/s41564-019-0481-y***]]></description>
